 Hampshire]]\n|{{sort|19920109|January 9, 1992}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=COURANT/><ref>{{Cite web | title = Vermont Men's Basketball Records | publisher = [[University of Vermont]] | url = http://www.uvm.edu/~sportspr/mens_basketball/?Page=bkbhistoryandrecords.html#game-ind | accessdate = June 1, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|13\n|{{sortname|Hassan|Whiteside}}\n|C\n|{{sort|1|Fr}}\n|[[Marshall Thundering Herd men's basketball|Marshall]]\n|[[UCF Knights men's basketball|UCF]]\n|{{sort|20100227|February 27, 2010}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref name=THRU2016/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://herdzone.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030810aab.html | title=Hassan Whiteside Earns Three More Awards from Sporting News | publisher=[[Marshall University]] | accessdate=June 1, 2010 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929114930/http://herdzone.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/030810aab.html | archive-date=September 29, 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n|13\n|{{sortname|Sean|Williams|dab=basketball}}\n|F/C\n|{{sort|3|Jr}}\n|[[Boston College Eagles men's basketball|Boston College]]\n|[[Duquesne Dukes men's basketball|Duquesne]]\n|{{sort|20061228|December 28, 2006}}\n|align=\"center\"|<ref>{{cite web | url=http://bceagles.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/williams_sean00.html | title=Sean Williams player profile | publisher=[[Boston College]] | accessdate=June 1, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100429205836/http://bceagles.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/williams_sean00.html | archivedate=April 29, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/player/profile?playerId=22199 | title=Sean Williams stats | publisher=[[ESPN.com]] | accessdate=June 1, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of National Basketball Association players with most blocks in a game]]\n\n==References==\n;General\n*{{Cite web |title=2018\u201319 NCAA Men's Basketball Records |publisher=[[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] |date=2018 |url=http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/m_basketball_RB/2019/D1.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=February 4, 2019}}\n\n;Specific\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{NCAA Division I men's basketball statistical leaders}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Blocks, 13}}\n[[Category:NCAA Division I men's basketball statistical leaders]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bradley, Shawn (2008) 2.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[Shawn Bradley]] is tied for second all-time in single game blocks (14).]]\nIn [[basketball]], a [[block (basketball)|block]] (short for blocked shot) occurs when a defender deflects or stops a [[field goal (basketball)|field goal]] attempt without committing a [[personal foul (basketball)|foul]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/baskBasi/glos.asp|title=Basketball glossary|work=FIBA.com|accessdate=May 24, 2010}}</ref> The [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]]'s (NCAA) [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] players on this list all accomplished the rare feat of blocking 13 shots in a single game. The 1985\u201386 season was the first that statistics on blocks were first compiled by the NCAA.<ref name=NCAA>{{Cite web | title = 2009\u201310 NCAA Men's Basketball Records | work = 2009\u201310 NCAA Men's Basketball Media Guide | publisher = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] | date = 2009 | url = http://web1.ncaa.org/web_files/stats/m_basketball_RB/2010/D1.pdf | format = PDF | accessdate = June 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe highest single game block total by one player in NCAA Division I men's basketball history is 16, set by [[Mickell Gladness]] of [[Alabama A&M Bulldogs men's basketball|Alabama A&M]] on February 24, 2007 against [[Texas Southern Tigers men's basketball|Texas Southern]].<ref name=MICKELL1>{{cite web | url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/player/profile?playerId=28001 | title=Mickell Gladness stats | publisher=[[ESPN.com]] | accessdate=June 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=MICKELL2>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/sports/richmond-defeats-massachusetts-70-63-in-ot-81398712.html | title=Richmond defeats Massachusetts 70-63 in OT | magazine=[[Washington Examiner]] | date=January 13, 2010 | accessdate=June 1, 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=March 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Although Gladness holds the single-game record, it is [[Jarvis Varnado]] of [[Mississippi State Bulldogs men's basketball|Mississippi State]] who claims the all-time career blocked shots record (564).<ref name=VARNADO>{{cite news | last = Gardner | first = Tim | url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/campusrivalry/post/2010/02/mississippi-states-jarvis-varnado-blocks-his-way-into-ncaa-record-books/1 | title=Mississippi State's Jarvis Varnado blocks his way into NCAA record books | date= February 25, 2010 | newspaper=[[USA Today]] | accessdate=May 25, 2010}}</ref> Varnado never blocked 13 or more shots in a game, however.<ref name=NCAA/> Through the [[2015\u201316 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2015\u201316 season]], only 18&nbsp;different players have reached the 13-block mark.<ref name=NCAA/><ref name=THRU2016>{{Cite web | title = 2016\u201317 NCAA Division I Blocked Shots (single game) | work = NCAA.com | publisher = [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] | url = http://fs.ncaa.org/Docs/stats/m_basketball_RB/2017/D1.pdf | accessdate = March 16, 2017}}</ref> Among them, Gladness is the only player to have reached 16 blocks, nobody has blocked 15, five players have reached 14, and twelve players have hit 13&nbsp;blocks.\n\n[[David Robinson (basketball)|David Robinson]] once blocked 14 shots in a game while playing for [[Navy Midshipmen men's basketball|Navy]], and is the only player on this list to be inducted into the [[Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.hoophall.com/hall-of-famers/tag/david-robinson | title=David Robinson | publisher=Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame | work=hoophall.com | year=2009 | accessdate=June 1, 2010 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091107121559/http://www.hoophall.com/hall-of-famers/tag/david-robinson | archivedate=November 7, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn the era before blocks were officially tracked by the entire NCAA, on December 3, 1983, [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] blocked 16 shots in a game while playing for the University of [[1983\u201384 Houston Cougars men's basketball team|Houston]] against Biscayne.  The blocks are a school record and would have tied the NCAA Division I record.  Like Robinson, Olajuwon has also been inducted into the Basketball Hall of Fame.<ref>{{cite news|title=Olajuwon has 16 blocks as Houston wins, 69-51|date=December 4, 1983|first=Bob|last=McSpadden|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|page=16B}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1950s [[Bill Russell]]'s shot-blocking ability was touted in his junior and senior year, but there were no official statistics of blocks then and scant film of survives from his college career. However, in his last game as a college player (in which his University of San Francisco team clinched the NCAA championship for the second year in a row to cap an undefeated season) film does exist and Russell is unofficially credited with 20 blocked shots in that game (to go with 26 points and 27 rebounds, a double-[[triple-double]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/sports/blogs/1955-56-San-Francisco-Team-Profile.html|first=Bob, Jr.|last=Vetrone|quote=Russell totaled 26 points, 27 rebounds and 20 blocked shots in the title game|title=1955\u201356 San Francisco Team Profile|newspaper=The Philadelphia Inquirer|date=March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the 70-71 season, Jim Farr of Univerisity of Mississippi unofficially had 15 block shots vs University of Southern Mississippi and followed by 12 blocks vs Auburn in the very next game.  This also was part of a triple double (16pts, 16reb, 12 blocks).\n\n==Key==\n{{col-start}}{{col-break|width=50%}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|'''Pos.'''||G||F||C||'''Ref.'''\n|-\n|[[Basketball position|Position]]||[[Basketball position#Backc